{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586140"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:26:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15066"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15066"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.04,0.27,0,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18932"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMembranous glomerulonephritis is characterised by immune complex deposition in the glomerular basement membrane. The condition can be primary (idiopathic) or secondary to underlying systemic diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most commonly associated with secondary membranous glomerulonephritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis B infection","Hepatitis A infection","Rheumatoid arthritis","Multiple sclerosis","Type 1 diabetes mellitus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESecondary membranous glomerulonephritis can be caused by several underlying conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E infection is one of the most common causes worldwide, particularly in endemic regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is a self-limiting infection that rarely causes renal complications\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E more commonly causes other forms of glomerulonephritis such as mesangial proliferative glomerulonephritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with glomerular disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E causes diabetic nephropathy rather than membranous glomerulonephritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important causes of secondary membranous glomerulonephritis include systemic lupus erythematosus, solid organ malignancies (especially lung and colon), and certain medications (such as penicillamine and gold).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Membranous glomerulonephritis is characterised by subepithelial immune complex deposits along the glomerular basement membrane","Common causes of secondary membranous glomerulonephritis include hepatitis B infection, systemic lupus erythematosus, and solid organ malignancies","Primary (idiopathic) membranous glomerulonephritis is associated with anti-phospholipase A2 receptor antibodies"],"references":["Ronco P, Beck L, Debiec H, Fervenza FC, Hou FF, Jha V, Sethi S, Tong A, Vivarelli M, Wetzels J. Membranous nephropathy. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2021 Sep 30;7(1):69. doi: 10.1038/s41572-021-00303-z. PMID: 34593809.","Alok A, Yadav A. Membranous Nephropathy. 2023 Jun 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32644595.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15066"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T22:27:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T22:28:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7754"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"